textDisplay: We don't need to worry about polls or votes. We just need to make sure that democrats do not steal the election again using all the tricks in the book. If you think the las election was fair, you live in another galaxy. There were a lot of results that changed from late election night to the next morning. For example: On election night, a little past midnight, Trump was ahead in PA by 600K votes. The vote-counting center closed at this time to re-open in the morning. When I got up the next morning at 8am, Biden was ahead by 100K... Where did those 700K came from while the vote-counting center was closed? You know the answer.  Another example... In NV there are 17 counties. Trump won in 15 counties. Biden won in 2 counties. It just happened that the counties that Biden won are the 2 counties that basically had all the population in NV. To make it more interesting, while Trump won by a normal margin (e.g. 53% vs 47%) Biden won those two counties by an astronomical margin, basically 80% vs 20%!!! Also, While CA (pop. 40M) and NY (pop. 20M) reported election results the same night, NV (pop. 3M) took a week to report the final results! The same phenomenon was repeated in AZ, MI, and WI. In all these states Biden won by a very small margin, and all of them were swing states! Common sense should tell you what happened here.

textDisplay: Ok so that's why they call it random sample polling but statistical methodology in politics tends to be very accurate for the most part. Gallup for example has predicted every single out of a presidential election going back to Truman vs Dewey in 48 where they missed. The only reason they missed it then was because at that time the last polling data going in the election was conducted a full month before. Nowadays polling is conducted all the way till the last day preceeding and election. Gallup even predicted the popular vote of 2000 election and 2016. Polling can be very accurate if conducted correctly and by organizations that know what they're doing. It's important to always look at the margin of error in every poll. If it's more than +/- 3% take it with a grain of salt..
textOriginal: Ok so that's why they call it random sample polling but statistical methodology in politics tends to be very accurate for the most part. 2. There is no significant primary contest for the incumbent - TRUE (1-1)
3. The incumbent is seeking re-election - TRUE (2-1 Biden)
4. There is no significant third party challenger - TRUE (3-1 Biden)
5. Short-term economy isn't in recession - TRUE (4-1 Biden)
6. Long-term economy is strong - TRUE (5-1 Biden)
7. The incumbent has directed major policy change that has affected the country's future - TRUE (6-1 Biden)
8. No widespread violent social unrest - TRUE; the wars in Ukraine and Gaza have led to unrest but it has been peaceful protesting all around. (7-1 Biden)
9. No scandal - TRUE (8-1 Biden)
10. No foreign/military failure - FALSE; the Afghan withdraw was indeed a failure. (8-2 Biden)

12. Charismatic incumbent - FALSE (9-3 Biden)

C9. 'I don't trust the polls, I have never been polled and nor has my 18 year old daughter!'

FACTS: Every poll covers about 0.001% of the voting population of America.  So even if everyone had an equal chance of being polled, the average person would be waiting 10000 polls on average between being contacted - or say a few thousand after adjusting for non-responses. There are often about 100 national voting intention polls per year.  Especially if one lives in a boring seat that doesn't get a lot of seat polls, one might get polled only a few times in one's voting life, if that.

A2: "polls generally only reach older voters because younger voters do not have landlines or answer mobile phone calls from unknown numbers"

FACTS: No major regular voting intention pollster exclusively uses phone polling. Most are exclusively online and therefore do not call at all.  Some less prominent polls still use phone polling but phone polling of random numbers is not very accurate anymore because younger voters are so hard to reach and those who are reached tend to be unrepresentative.

textDisplay: I actually think this polling is probably pretty accurate, though it does deserve some context. That makes sense as pretty much everyone I know who voted for Trump in 2016 and 2020 love him more than ever, so that part of the polling seems accurate. What is different between the 2020 election results and these polls is Biden's support in each of these states has drastically gone down. The question will be is this part an error in the polling or is this accurate, which we won't know until election day.
